sec.p:
Catalysis by allene oxide synthases (CYP74A and CYP74 
C
): Alterations by the Phe/Leu mutation at the SRS-1 region

The CYP74 family of cytochromes P450 includes four fatty acid hydroperoxide metabolizing enzymes: allene oxide synthase ( AOS ), hydroperoxide lyase ( HPL ), divinyl ether synthase, and epoxyalcohol synthase ( EAS ). All P450s have six substrate recognition sites (SRSs) in their structures. Some CYP74 mutations in SRSs leading to their interconversions including substitutions in “ F / L toggle” (SRS-1 region) were reported before. For further elucidation of the role of this site in CYP74 catalysis, the effect of Phe/Leu mutation on the specificity of selected AOSs was studied in the present work. Mutant forms of ZmAOS1 (CYP74A19,
Zea mays
), LeAOS3 (CYP74 C 3,
Lycopersicon esculentum
), and PpAOS2 (CYP74A8,
Physcomitrella patens
) acquired partial EAS activity. Mutant forms of ZmAOS1 and PpAOS2 possessed additional HPL activities. The results validate the significance of the “ F / L toggle” as a catalytic determinant of CYP74s, as well as the importance of the conserved Phe at this site for the AOS catalysis.

Cytochromes P450 are the haem-thiolate enzymes involved in numerous biosynthetic and xenobiotic pathways found in all organisms except obligate anaerobes (

; 

). Majority of cytochromes P450 are monooxygenases (classical P450s). These enzymes oxidising the hydrophobic molecules use the dioxygen molecule as a second substrate and interact with the electron transfer chains (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). In contrast, the nonclassical P450s, converting the peroxides of hydrophobic compounds, are independent of dioxygen and electron carriers. These are, for instance, the prostacyclin (PGI 
2
) and thromboxane (TXA 
2
) synthases of mammals and other metazoans (

) and CYP74 clan proteins of plants, some non-mammals, algae and proteobacteria (

). The CYP74 enzymes control the isomerisation or dehydration of fatty acid hydroperoxides to various bioactive oxylipins. Four 
types
of CYP74 clan enzymes are currently known, namely two dehydrases, allene oxide synthase (
AOS
) and divinyl ether synthase (
DES
), and two isomerases, hydroperoxide lyase (
HPL
, synonym: hemiacetal synthase (

)) and epoxyalcohol synthase (
EAS
).

Several catalytically significant regions called the substrate recognition sites (SRSs) have been uncovered within the P450 primary structure (

; 

; 

). Some of them constitute the walls of the catalytic cavity, for instance, the I-helix (

; 

; 

). Furthermore, the experiments on site-directed mutagenesis revealed some primary determinants within the SRSs, which govern the 
type
of catalysis (

; 

; 

; 

; 

, 

, 

). One of these determinants, namely the Phe 137, was uncovered from the 3D-structure of 

Arabidopsis thaliana

AOS (AtAOS, CYP74A1) (

). This site is localised at the distal face of haem iron. Phe residue as this site in 
AOS
sequences controls reactivity of epoxyallylic radical and its cation by reaction with an aromatic π- system (

). The 
F
137L mutant form of AtAOS exhibited mainly the 
HPL
activity (as well as the minor 
AOS
activity) in contrast to the WT enzyme (

). All studied AOSs have the conserved Phe residue at this site (referred to as “ 
F
/ 
L
toggle” (

)), while all HPLs and DESs have the Leu residue. The Leu/ Phe mutations at this site of selected CYP74 
C
HPLs led to a higher proportion of 
AOS
activity compared to the WT enzymes (

). For further elucidation of role of this putative determinant of kind of CYP74 enzymes catalysis, the effect of Phe/Leu mutations at “ 
F
/ 
L
toggle” on the specificity of selected AOSs (CYP74A and CYP74 
C
subfamilies) has been studied in the present work.

The WT enzymes, as well as their mutant forms, were incubated with fatty acid hydroperoxides. The NaBH 4 -reduced (as well as the non-reduced) products (Me/ TMS ) of incubations were analysed by GC-MS. The structural formulae of the identified products of target WT AOSs and their mutant forms are presented at Fig. 2 . All studied WT AOSs specifically produced the α- ketols (allene oxide hydrolysis products), which were identified as Me/ TMS derivatives by GC-MS. Respectively, the NaBH 4 -reduced products of the WT AOSs were represented predominantly by the nearly equal pairs of threo and erythro vic -diols (see the NaBH 4 -reduced products of WT LeAOS3 and its F 108 L mutant form as the examples, Fig. 3 ). For instance, the 9(
S
)- HPOD conversion by LeAOS3 afforded the α- ketol (12 Z )-9-hydroxy-10-oxo-12-octadecenoic acid (
), which upon the NaBH 4 reduction has been converted to the diastereomeric pair of 9,10-diols 1a and 1b ( Fig. 3A ), possessing the identical mass spectral patterns exhibiting M + at m/z 472 (0.11%), [ M – Me] + at m/z 457 (0.84%), [ M – MeO] + at m/z 441 (2.6%), [ M – C 11/ C 18] + at m/z 361 (12.19%), [ M – C 10/ C 18 + TMS ] + at m/z 332 (4.16%), [361 – TMSOH ] + at m/z 271 (66.31%), [ M – C 10/ C 18] + at m/z 259 (66.03%), [ M – C 1/ C 9] + at m/z 213 (40.40%), m/z 155 (64.93%), m/z 129 (32.80%), m/z 109 (25.36%) [ CH 2 = O + -SiMe 3 ] at m/z 103 (34.16%), TMS + m/z 73 (100%). Additional product of 9(
S
)- HPOD conversion by LeAOS3 was cyclopentenone, 10-oxo-11-phytoenoic acid (10-oxo-PEA), the NaBH 4 reduced derivative of which registered in GC-MS was compound 3 , the cyclopentanol 10-hydroxyphytonoic acid (Me/ TMS ). This product appeared as the diastereomeric pair of peaks with the retention time ca. 15.0 min ( Fig. 3A ). Additionally, the WT LeAOS3 produced a trace amount of 9-oxononanoic acid – 9- HPL product (
