Along with 9(
S
)- HPOD and 13(
S
)- HPOD , the WT ZmAOS1, PpAOS2, and LuAOS were also active towards the 9(
S
)- HPOT and 13(
S
)- HPOT as the substrates and converted them to the corresponding α− ketols, 9- hydroxy-10-oxo-12,15-octadecadienoic and 12-oxo-13-hydroxy-9,15- octadecadienoic acids, respectively ( Fig. 4 and Supplementary Fig. S1 ), the NaBH 4 reduction of which led to the formation of the diastereomeric pairs of 9,10-diols 2a -2b ( Fig. 4 ) and 12,13-diols 7a -7b (Supplementary Fig. S1 ), respectively.

Upon the incubation of LeAOS3 F 108L mutant form with 9(
S
)- HPOD , compound 4 was formed along with α- ketol and 10-oxo-PEA, as seen from the GC-MS analyses of NaBH 4 -reduced products (Me/ TMS ) presented in Fig. 3B (quantification data for the reaction products of all mutant forms are presented in Table 2 ). The mass spectrum of compound 4 exhibited M + at m/z 398 (0.15%); [ M – Me] + at m/z 383 (0.93%); [ M – C 1/ C 8] + at m/z 241 (2.29%); [ M – C 1/ C 9] + at m/z 212 (3.20%); [ M – C 1/ C 10] + at m/z 199 (71.65%). A prominent peak at m/ z 199 indicated the presence of an oxiranyl carbinol function with oxirane at C 9/ C 10 and a secondary alcohol moiety ( TMS ) at C 11. The mass spectrum corresponded to that of 9,10-epoxy-11-hydroxy-12-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS ) (
). Catalytic hydrogenation of product 4 over PtO 2 followed by methylation and trimethylsilylation afforded product, mass spectrum of which indicated a structure of 9,10-epoxy-11-hydroxyoctadecanoic acid (Me/ TMS ). Thus, the mass spectral data substantiated the structure of 9,10-epoxy-11- hydroxy-12-octadecenoic acid for compound 4 .

Incubation of LeAOS3 F 108 L mutant form with 13(
S
)- HPOD resulted in appearance of major peaks 8a-8b , while as 12,13-diols ( AOS product) and products 10a-10c were minor products ( Fig. 3D ). The mass spectrum of compounds 8a and 8b were nearly identical and possessed M + at m/z 398 (0.10%); [ M – Me] + at m/z 383 (2.11%); [ M – n -pentyl] + at m/z 327 (0.83%); [ M – C 12/ C 18] + at m/z 285 (63.45%); [ TMS ] + at m/z 73 (100%). A prominent fragment [ M – C 12/ C 18] + at m/z 285 resulted from cleavage between oxirane and C 11 (
), thus substantiating the structure of 11-hydroxy-12,13- epoxy-9-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS ) – epoxyalcohol oxiranyl carbinol ( EAS product). Catalytic hydrogenation of products 8a and 8b over PtO 2 followed by methylation and trimethylsilylation yielded saturated analogue, possessing the mass spectrum corresponded to the structure of 11-hydroxy-12,13-epoxyoctadecanoic acid (Me/ TMS ), thus confirming the identification of compounds 8a and 8b as EAS products.

The mass spectra of compounds 10a-10c ( Fig. 3D ) (Me/ TMS ) were also nearly identical and exhibited M + at m/z 398 (0.29%); [ M – Me] + at m/z 383 (0.96%); [ M – MeOH] + at m/z 367 (0.43%); [ M – C 1/ C 8] + at m/z 241 (33.02%); [ M – C 1/ C 12 + TMS ] + at m/z 173 (6.03%); [ CH 2 = O + – TMS ] at m/z 103 (17.01%); [ M – C 1/ C 12 – H] + at m/z 99 (57.67%); [ TMS ] + at m/z 73 (100%). A prominent peak at m/z 99 indicated the cleavage of oxirane at C 12/ C 13, as well as large peak m/z 241 corresponded to secondary alcohol ( TMS ) function at C 9. As a whole, the mass spectrum corresponded to that of (10 E )-9-hydroxy-12,13-epoxy-10-octadecenoic acid (Me/ТМS) (
) – epoxyalcohol oxiranyl vinyl carbinol (also EAS product). Catalytic hydrogenation converted products 10a-10c into a saturated analogue, the mass spectrum of which approved the structures of 9- hydroxy-12,13-epoxyoctadecanoic acid (Me/ TMS ) for the hydrogenated product, and 9-hydroxy-12,13-epoxy-10-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS ) for compounds 10a-10c . Thus, LeAOS3 F 108 L mutant form possessed mixed AOS / EAS activity, and EAS activity was the main when mutant form was incubating with 13(
S
)- HPOD . At the same time, HPL activity of LeAOS3 F 108 L was the same with that of WT enzyme. The mutant form possessed trace 9- HPL (in the same amount as the WT LeAOS3 did) and no 13- HPL activities.

The mass spectrum of compound 12 ( Fig. 5B ), the product of 9( S )- HPOD conversion by the PpAOS2 F93 L mutant form, possessed M + at m/z 398 (0.1%), [M + – Me] at m/z 383 (0.7%), [M + – MeO] at m/z 367 (0.5%), [M + – Me( CH 2 ) 4 ] at m/z 327 (14%), [M + – TMSOH] + at m/z 308 (2%), [327 – TMSOH] + at m/z 237 (14%), [M + – C10/C18] at m/z 185 (22%), [M + – C1/C12] at m/z 173 (10%), m/z 125 (12%), m/z 97 (16%), m/z 75 (39%), [SiMe 3 ] + at m/z 73 (100%). The spectrum was similar to that of compound 11 and indicated the structure of the oxiranyl vinyl carbinol 9,10-epoxy-13-hydroxy-11-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS) – EAS product – for compound 12 . The mass spectrum of additional 9( S )-HPOD conversion product 4 ( Fig. 5B ), 9 and 10-epoxy-11- hydroxy-12-octadecenoic acid (Me/TMS) – also EAS product, is described above. Thus, the main activity of the PpAOS2 F93 L mutant form towards 9-hydroperoxides was EAS activity. Besides, little amounts of compound 13 were also detected after the PpAOS2 F93 L mutant form incubations with 9( S )-HPOT ( Fig. 4B ) and 9( S )-HPOD ( Fig. 5B ). The mass spectrum of product 13 (not presented) matched that for 9-hydroxynonanoic acid (Me/TMS) (
), thus demonstrating the formation of 9-oxononanoic acid via the 9-HPL route. The 9-oxononanoic acid (its mass spectrum matched that described by
) was also detected when the non-reduced products (Me/TMS) were subjected to the GC-MS analyses.

Some primary determinants of catalysis by CYP74 enzymes have been revealed previously (
;
,
,
). Substitution of the conserved amino acids at these sites might change the type of catalysis. One of these catalytic determinants, the “ F / L toggle” (SRS-1), was uncovered thanks to the X-ray 3D-structural analysis of
A. thaliana AOS
(AtAOS, CYP74A1) (
). Importance of this site was confirmed by the conversion of the AOS to HPL activity upon Phe to Leu substitution by site-directed mutagenesis (
). Nonetheless, the attempts of the Authors of work (
) to make a reverse conversion by the Leu to Phe mutation at this site of HPL have failed (personal communication). The results of the present work provide new evidence for the catalytic significance of the “ F / L toggle” (SRS-1) for the catalysis of CYP74 enzymes.

The mutant forms LeAOS3 F 108 L , ZmAOS1 F 95 L , and PpAOS2 F 93 L possessed the altered product specificities and converted the substrates, (9(
S
)- HPOD , 9(
S
)- HPOT , 13(
S
)- HPOD , and 13(
S
)- HPOT ), into the epoxyalcohols (the EAS products) along with α- ketols ( Figs. 3–5 and Supplementary Figs. S1–S 2 ). For instance, the LeAOS3 F 108 L mutant form exhibited the dual AOS / EAS activity possessing mainly AOS activity (87.3%) towards preferred substrate – 9(
S
)- HPOD and mainly EAS activity (77.5%) towards non-preferred substrate – 13(
S
)- HPOD . Furthermore, some mutant forms possessed also the HPL activity. The ZmAOS1 F 95 L mutant form possessed mainly the AOS or HPL activities being incubated with 9(
S
)- HPOD /T (53.8% and 59.4%, respectively) or 13(
S
)- HPOD /T (47.0% and 58.6%, respectively). The EAS activity of this mutant form was minor towards all examined hydroperoxides. The PpAOS2 F 93 L mutant form possessed almost only EAS activity towards 9-hydroperoxides, while as HPL (43.2%) or AOS (58.6%) activities towards 13(
S
)- HPOD and 13(
S
)- HPOT , respectively. In contrast to other studied enzymes, the LuAOS F 155 L mutant form kept the unaltered AOS activity.

The results of the present work confirmed the importance of the “ F / L toggle” as the determinant of CYP74 catalysis. At the same time, the above-described data showed that the Phe to Leu replacement at this site of different AOSs does not necessarily lead to a creation of HPL activity. One of the studied enzymes, the LuAOS (CYP74A1) retained the AOS activity upon the F 155 L mutation. In contrast, the Phe/Leu mutant forms of three other AOSs, ZmAOS1, LeAOS3 and PpAOS2, possessed the significant changes of catalysis. The LeAOS3 F 108 L mutation resulted in partial AOS to EAS conversion. In turn, the ZmAOS1 F 95 L mutant form acquired the partial HPL activity. Finally, the PpAOS2 F 93 L mutant form possessed the altered catalysis and behaved largely as the EAS toward the 9-hydroperoxides and HPL toward the 13- HPOD . Moreover, 9- HPOD and 9- HPOT conversions by the EAS activity of the PpAOS2 F 93 L mutant form resulted in formation of oxiranyl vinyl carbinols as main products, whereas normally EASs produce mainly oxiranyl carbinols (
;
, b, 2018a, b, 2019).

Conversions of AOSs to HPLs by site-directed mutagenesis at several sites (including the SRS-1 (

), the I-helix groove (

), and the ERR triad (

)) have been described earlier. The results of the present work show that the same mutation causing the nearly complete 
AOS
to 
HPL
conversion with some enzymes does not necessarily lead to identical conversions in case of different proteins. Moreover, the same mutation may exceptionally have no consequences in the case of some proteins.

The present report described partial AOS into EAS conversion upon the site-directed mutagenesis. Some conversions of CYP74 enzymes catalysis caused by the site-directed mutagenesis, namely the AOS to HPL conversions (
;
,
), DES to AOS (
) and double function HPL / EAS (CYP74 C ) to AOS (
), have been described before. It is noteworthy in this connection that some plant AOSs produce the epoxyalcohols as the minor side products (
,b). All these data demonstrate the versatility of CYP74 catalysis, capability of CYP74 enzymes to undergo interconversions. The 18 O 2 labelling experiments with AOS (
), DES (
), HPL (
;
) and EAS (
, b) showed the rearrangement mechanism proceeding via the epoxyallylic radical, which is a general intermediate of all CYP74 enzymes ( Fig. 6 ). Final transformations of the epoxyallylic radical occur either via a loss of a proton ( AOS , DES ), or the recombination of the epoxyallylic radical ( EAS ), or the vinyloxycarbinyl radical ( HPL ) with hydroxyl radical ( Fig. 6 ). Thus, four distinct types of catalytic activity are controlled by CYP74 enzymes, which are structurally and phylogenetically related. Their kinship creates the prerequisites for the conversion of the type of catalysis by the site-directed mutagenesis.

Linoleic and α- linolenic acids, as well as the soybean lipoxygenase type V, were purchased from Sigma. NaBH 4 and silylating reagents were purchased from Fluka (Buchs, Switzerland ). (9
S
,10 E ,12 Z )-9- Hydroperoxy-10,12-octadecadienoic acid (9(
S
)- HPOD ) and (9
S
,10 E ,12 Z ,15 Z )-9-hydroperoxy-10,12,15-octadecatrienoic acid (9(
S
)- HPOT ) were prepared by incubation of linoleic and α- linolenic acids, respectively, with the recombinant maize 9-lipoxygenase (GeneBank:AAG61118.1) (
) in Na-phosphate buffer (100 mM, pH 6.0) at 0 ̊ C , under continuous oxygen bubbling. (9 Z ,11 E ,13
S
)-13-Hydroperoxy-9,11-octadecadienoic acid (13(
S
)- HPOD ) and (9 Z ,11 E ,13
S
,15 Z )-13-hydroperoxy-9,11,15-octadecatrienoic acid (13(
S
)- HPOT ) were obtained by incubation of linoleic and α- linolenic acids, respectively, with the soybean lipoxygenase type V in Tris-HCl buffer (50 mM, pH 9.0) at 23 ̊ C , under continuous oxygen bubbling. The extracted hydroperoxides (as free carboxylic acids) were purified by normal phase HPLC on Macherey-Nagel Nucleodur 100-3 silica column (250 × 4.6 mm , 3 μm) under the isocratic elution with the solvent mixture hexane/isopropanol/acetic acid (98.1:1.8:0.1, v/v) at a flow rate of 0.4 ml/min. Hydroperoxides were chromatographically pure and at least 98% optically pure, as judged by chiral phase HPLC (
).

The recombinant WT enzymes and their mutant forms (10 μg) were incubated with 100 μg of 9(
S
)- HPOD , 9(
S
)- HPOT , 13(
S
)- HPOD , or 13(
S
)- HPOT in Na-phosphate buffer (100 mM, 10 ml), pH 7.0, 23 ̊ C , for 15 min. The reaction mixtures were acidified to pH 6.0, and the products were extracted with hexane/ethyl acetate (1:1, v/v) mixture, then methylated with ethereal diazomethane and trimethylsilylated with pyridine/hexamethyldisilazane/trimethylchlorosilane (1:1:1, v/v) mixture at 23 ̊ C for 30 min. The silylation reagents were evaporated in vacuo. The dry residue was dissolved in 100 μl of hexane and subjected to GC-MS analyses. When specified, the products were reduced with NaBH 4 , then methylated and trimethylsilylated. Alternatively, the products of NaBH 4 reduction were hydrogenated over PtO 2 , then methylated and trimethylsilylated. Products (without or with the preliminary NaBH 4 reduction) were analysed as Me esters/ TMS derivatives (Me/ TMS ) by GC-MS as described before (
).

